      "text": "After reading about the M1 speculation issue in ARM ([/Risks/33/28 Risks 33.28]) I was reminded I had read something similar previously. My recollection was wrong, but it did eventually get to a point.  [https://www.hertzbleed.com/ https://www.hertzbleed.com/] demonstrated a side channel attack against most popular x86 chips. I don't specialize in chipsets, and tend towards having to believe when I ask the silicon for (1 | 0 ) it will almost never answer 2, or give give my private key to someone strolling by.  Seems like the industry was already aware there were some side channel issues in DVFS, as CLKSCREW demonstrated as early as 2017. [https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/security/clkscrew-attack-can-hack-modern-chipsets-via-their-power-management-features/ https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/security/clkscrew-attack-can-hack-modern-chipsets-via-their-power-management-features/]"
